1. --
{ Welcome to the King's Indian Attack world!  This is my 3rd course for Chessable and as the title suggests it is about the King's Indian Attack  (KIA)  . What is KIA? It is a system of playing for White which is characterized by moves 1. e4 2. d3 3. Nd2 4. Ngf3 5. g3 6. Bg2 7. O-O. It can also be reached via different move orders but the most popular alternative to 1. e4 + 2. d3 etc. is 1. Nf3 2. g3 3. Bg2 4. O-O 5. d3 6. Nbd2 7. e4. In many cases, these positions will transpose to each other but both of them have some pros and cons:  a  1. e4 move order:  PROS:  - White avoids   1.Nf3  d5  which is not to everybody's taste  - This is the move order usually chosen by modern KIA player  - You can use it as a weapon vs for example the Sicilian and French while sticking to your favourite lines in other openings  CONS  - White has to allow   1.e4  e5  and   1.e4  d5  which are not ideal openings for the KIA set-up  b  1.Nf3 move order:  PROS:  - White avoids   1.e4  e5  and   1.e4  d5  so he is guaranteed to reach the KIA setup  - Ideal for the King's Indian Defence players  CONS:  - White allows   1.Nf3  d5  where Black can choose from multiple setups such as  2.g3  Nf6  3.Bg2  Bg4  (reversed Torre)  or 3... Bf5  (reversed London)  or 3... c5  (reversed KID)  .  - Black has some additional options such as 1... f5  All in all, it wasn't an easy decision but I decided to stick to the 1.e4 move order. The biggest reason is that the reversed Torre and the reversed London are not to everyone's taste and I thought I will follow a 'pure' form of the KIA which was favoured by Bobby Fischer and the best chess coach in history, Mark Dvoretsky. I started to play the King's Indian Attack regularly around 3 years ago. I fell in love with that opening when watching Hikaru Nakamura's streams. Firstly, I started employing this setup in the faster time control games but later I discovered that it is a perfect weapon for beating lower-rated players. Why is that the case? You will reach certain types of positions when you play this opening. Very rarely you will see piece exchanges and in many cases, even pawns won't be exchanged. That means that your opponent can't easily simplify the position and you will have a ton of chances to outplay him in the middlegame or in the endgame. Also, he won't be able to prepare with computer-like variations, because the positions will be just equal and there are almost no forced lines - with some exceptions of course. If you add the fact that in many cases your opponent will have a decent repertoire after 1.d4 and 1.e4  (main lines)  it is very likely that after you employ the KIA setup he may be forced to enter the unfamiliar territory. If you combine these aspects of the KIA, it is obvious that your lower-rated opponents will hate it since they can't out prepare you in the main line Najdorf. But I'd like to give you a small warning! This opening is usually perfect when you face a lower-rated or equal opponent. Whenever you play someone much stronger it is not a bad weapon but now it is your opponent who probably wants to avoid exchanges and outplay you in an equal position. Don't get me wrong! It is a good opening to use even against a higher-rated opponent but I can imagine that he will be more afraid of some more aggressive lines. Before I present you a list of some pros of this system let me just inform you that in most of the lines Black will be objectively equal. That means that if he doesn't commit any mistake you won't be able to win the game. But when you think about it, it is a case with all of the openings! The difference is that in most of the KIA variations, White scores 60%+. That means, that in practice it is unavoidable for Black not to go wrong. Now some pros:  - The King's Indian Attack was used by Bobby Fischer who claimed that this is a really good opening vs systems with ... e6. He scored a few brilliant victories and some of his games are annotated in the 'Model Games' chapter.  - Another positive aspect of playing the KIA setup is that you will reach it in every game with the White pieces while Black will witness this setup in like 2-3% of his games. That means that you will have like 30-40 times bigger experience than your villain colleague.  - Also, if you are a person who puts King's safety as his priority - if that is a case for you, we are in the same team! - you are guaranteed to have a safe King in this opening. If Black ever tries to launch a razor-sharp attack on your Monarch you will punish very quickly. I promise! No attacks on your King! These are always objectively bad for your opponent!  - This opening should suit players with a dynamic positional style but there is something about the KIA that some players may find very helpful. This opening is based more on plans and understanding than precise calculations. Of course, there will be positions where nothing can substitute precise calculations, but these cases will be quite rare; or at least much more rare than in the mainstream openings.  - I think that the KIA is a perfect practical weapon for classical chess, but for rapid and blitz - it is a real killer! You will be familiar with plans and ideas and in most cases, you will be able to save time on the clock. On the other hand, your opponent will usually waste time to try to come up with a sensible plan, which is not easy in this opening.  - Another positive aspect of this opening is that when you make an inaccuracy or a mistake it usually means that you either lose the initiative or just guarantee equal chances for your opponent. On the other hand, if Black goes wrong - he is often mated. Take a look at some of the model games where the French Defence was played. Black is often dead after only one mistake.  There are many strong players that used the KIA in their careers but I think that a player that deserves the most praise is GM Amin Bassem from Egypt. He plays this opening regularly against top players with outstanding results. It shouldn't surprise you that many of his games are analysed in the 'Model games' chapter.  Now some non-chess related things:  - There is a video recorded for the course. I think it may be a nice addition for some of you and as a bonus, you have a golden opportunity to see me in a jacket! Normally, I'd go with my Adidas slav clothing but sometimes you need to sacrifice a part of you for a bigger reason!  - There are arrows added and I will quickly explain my chosen colours:  green - ideas and plans  blue - also ideas and plans, but the ones that have a very high chance of being played next  red - careful, it's hot! Don't touch that! The same rule applies here, you see something red? It is wrong.  yellow - with this colour I marked secondary plans or additional ideas. Sometimes there are two plans in the position so one of them is usually blue and the other one is yellow.  In the end, I want to say that there are two lines for which I suggested two different approaches. One of them is   1.e4  c6  2.d3  d5  3.Nd2  e5  4.Ngf3  Bd6  and now:   - 5. g3 - a traditional and natural way of playing the position  - 5. d4!? a more modern and higher scoring approach  The other line that I've added is   1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.d3  and whenever Black goes for ... d5 we play Qe2 instead of more natural and more popular Nbd2. I devoted a whole chapter called 'KIA vs Sicilian - 2...e6 lines with Qe2' to this great variation which is probably my favourite line in the whole course.  There are a lot of annotated games added to this course. There are 37 annotated model games, usually played by strong grandmasters. I also added a chapter with my KIA games - there are 16 of them. If you want to laugh - taking a look at my games it is a great opportunity!  Finally, I will mention that in the 'French' chapters I mention the Plan A and Plan B quite often. I explain what I mean by that in the theory section a couple of times but if you decide to look at the variations randomly not step by step, then it may be unfamiliar for you. So here I provide you with brief explanations: In positions similar to 1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Be7 7.O-O O-O 8. Re1 b5 9. e5 Nd7, the Plan A is an attacking scheme for White based on the moves Nd2-f1 + h2-h4 + Nf1-h2-g4 followed by h4-h5-h6 - with or without Bf4 included. The Plan B is to play h2-h4 followed by Ng5 and Qh5 but it is usually less effective due to the GM Uhlmann's discovery which you can see in the second and the third line of the 3rd chapter - about French Main Line.  I really hope that you will love this opening as much as I do. I think it should be clear but let me mention that all of the lines have been thoroughly checked with the Stockfish chess engine.  Sincerely  FM Kamil 'Kaldas90' Plichta }
