1. e4 e6
{ The French Defence is the 3rd most popular opening against 1. e4. When I think about the King's Indian Attack - KIA - after 1. e4, it is this opening that comes into my mind. The great Bobby Fischer played a few games vs that tough-to-crack defence scoring remarkable victories. I decided that it is worth starting with 1... e6 so here we go. }
2. d3
{ Of course, if you want to play the KIA, you need to start with this move.  2.g3 ?!  d5  and White doesn't have time for  3.d3  due to  3...dxe4  and Black will get Queens off the board - it is not what we want. }
2... d5
{ A 'French' move. 2... c5 would transpose to the e6 Sicilian - Chapter #5. }
3. Nd2
{ Just in time. Now, if Black decides to go for  3...dxe4  we can safely play  4.dxe4  and the Knight on  d2  is very useful. }
3... Nf6
{ In practice, Black very often starts with this move. It is necessary to memorize arising variations - especially 4... Nc6 and 4... Bc5 - because we can't follow with our standard plans there. }
4. Ngf3 Nc6
{ A third most popular move after 4... c5 and 4... b6. It is necessary for you - dear reader - not to follow up stereotypically. }
5. c3
{ An excellent move. Note that  5.g3 ?!  is dubious because Black can play  5...dxe4  6.dxe4  Bc5  7.Bg2  O-O  8.O-O  e5  and Black's position has to be better due to great control over the centre. Databases confirm that statement giving Black around 60%! Please avoid this position.  A rule of thumb would be that if Black puts his piece on the c-file on move 4 - the same will happen in the 4... Nc6 line - then we can't play g3. }
5... a5
{ The most popular move. Black makes a waiting move to see what our plans are. If we play g3 he may stick to ... dxe4 followed by ...Bc5 and ...e5. }
6. e5
{ Playing in style of the reversed Philidor with 6. Be2 is also possible but I think not to my taste. }
6... Nd7 7. d4
{ We got a position similar to the Advance French with 3. e5. In fact, this is a very good version of the aforementioned opening because the Black Knight is misplaced on c6. It blocks Black's most typical French plan which is to play ...c5 undermining White's centre. }
7... f6
{ Being unable to strike with the c-pawn Black has to strike with the f-one to get any shade of counterplay. }
8. Bb5
{ I like this move a lot. We pin both of Black's Knights and indirectly fight for the e5-square combining that with development. }
8... fxe5 9. dxe5 Be7 10. Nd4
{ We break a basic rule here. Just please don't tell my parents. We shouldn't move the same piece twice in the opening but this position requires active measures. }
10... Ndxe5 { This is inaccurate due to } 11. f4
{ and Black has to go for a mediocre piece sacrifice with } 11... O-O 12. fxe5
Nxe5 13. N2f3
{ White will safely castle and if we don't have problems with our King here, then I am confident about our chances. }
