{ We would play this sooner or later so it is better to stick to it now. It is a useful waiting move. Note that  8.e5 ?!  would be premature due to  8...Nd7  9.Re1  Qc7  10.Qe2  Bb7  followed by long castling.  Black will be able to attack us on the kingside with moves such as . ..g5 or ...h5. Also, White's score in this line isn't particularly convincing so 8. Re1 is our move ! }
8... Bb7 9. a3
{ I really like this little move. We want to get our standard plan of going c2-c3 + a2-a3 forcing through b2-b4 but I think it is necessary to start with a3.   9.c3  allows Black to change his plans completely and play  9...O-O  after which  10.e5  Nd7  11.Nf1  b5  12.h4  is not that effective because Black can play  12...b4.  The pawn on c3 is a hook for Black's queenside actions and in the main line after 7... O-O we rarely play c3. That's why I prefer 9. a3 to see Black's idea. }
9... Qc7 10. c3
{ There is also an interesting line for reversed KID lovers.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nc4  with a typical reversed KID position.   Note that after  10.exd5  Black can't play  exd5 ?!  due to  11.b4 !  and now  cxb4 ?!  is bad for Black after  12.axb4  Nxb4  13.Ba3  O-O  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.c3  with a big advantage for White.   After  10.exd5  exd5 ?!  11.b4  the only chance for Black would be  11...O-O  but  12.bxc5  bxc5  13.Rb1  guarantees White a small edge.  I give you this line as an alternative if you like positions arising after exd5 Nxd5. }
10... dxe4
{ It is possible for Black to clarify the situation in the centre. White wasted some time playing a3 and c3 so it is quite a logical continuation. }
11. dxe4 O-O 12. Nc4
{ As I've already mentioned I don't like to commit to  12.e5  when the centre isn't stable. After  12...Nd7  13.Qe2  Rad8  14.h4  Black has a clear plan of playing ... a6 followed by ...b5 and ...c4. Then he will plant the Knight on c5 and eventually d3 - it is not my cup of tea. }
12... Rad8 13. Qb3
