{ Before we dig deeper into theoretical variations I want to show you White's basic attacking setup - plan A. It is marked by blue arrows. A secondary plan for White marked with yellow arrows is to play h2-h4 + Ng5 + Qh5 - plan B - but you need to watch out for Wolfgang Uhlmann's defensive concept which is analysed in the next two lines. Back to White's basic attacking plan which will be called a 'Plan A' in the rest of my repertoire. White starts with Nf1 and he will follow it up by h2-h4 Nf1-h2-g4 and h4-h5-h6 to attack Black's kingside weaknesses. Sometimes White will insert Bf4 in the process to support the e5-pawn. Black has a tough decision. If the White h-pawn reaches h6, it will create a lot of dark-squared weaknesses in the Black's camp. On the other hand, if he stops our expansion with ... h7-h6, his h6-pawn will be prone to all kinds of sacrifices.  Let me also mention that Black will look for counter chances on the other side of the board. We need to remember that whenever the Black pawn will land on a4, we need to respond with Fischer's a2-a3 patent. That avoids our queenside being weakened by ... a4-a3. It is funny because it is the same scenario that Black faces on the kingside but the fact that our King is on the kingside allows White to stop Black's expansion with this little a3 pawn thrust. }
