{ If you want to play the  3.g3  move order you have to be prepared to meet  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Nc3  Qe6+  6.Be2.  If the resulting position looks interesting to you, then I recommend taking a look at GM Munoz's games. }
3... g6 { 3...Nf6  4.g3  d5  5.exd5  transposes to the Reversed KID chapter. }
4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O e5
{ This setup is also possible and frankly quite popular. Black clamps on the centre and in some cases will try to force through the ...d6-d5 break. Also plans connected with ...f5 or ...b5 are possible. }
7. Nc3
{ Personally, I really like this setup. White abandons his usual c3 + a3 + b4 ideas and focuses on planting the Knight on d5. Note that the d5-square has been mortally weakened and White swifts his attention to that point of the board.   That being said, White can also play in a stereotypical way by  7.c3  Nge7  8.a3  O-O  9.b4  h6  10.Nbd2  Be6  11.Nb3  c4  12.dxc4  Bxc4  13.Re1  with a complicated battle ahead. }
7... Nge7 8. Nd2
{ White will increase his control over the centre with Nc4 to come next. Moving the Knight helped to increase the scope of our light-squared Bishop. True, it is behind the e-pawn at the moment but it secures the d5-outpost for the other Knight. Let me tell you that this setup was used by Mr Carlsen himself a couple of times. }
8... O-O 9. Nc4 Be6 10. Nd5
{ Just in time.  10.a4  would allow Black to play  10...d5.  White will play a2-a4 next followed by c2-c3 when our pieces and pawns take away all of the important squares from our opponent's pieces. }
10... Qd7 11. a4 f5 12. c3 { With f2-f4 and a4-a5 to come next. } *

