{ I want to cry when I see that the most popular moves are 9. Qe2, 9. Qb3 and 9. Bf1... 9. b4 ! is a way to go ! }
9... Bxf2+
{ 9...Be7  is a tough move to play but it was necessary. White would keep a nice advantage after  10.Bb2  O-O  11.a3 !  threatening Nd4 to trap the Black Queen after Bf1 ! Our opponent would need to decide for a very sad 11... Qd7 or 11... Qd8 followed by 12. e5 and O-O with a dominant position. 11... Nxe4 would lose in a similar way after 12. Bf1. }
10. Kxf2 Ng4+ 11. Ke1 Qc3
{ In the theoretical section I focused on 11... Ne3 so here we can analyse a different continuation. }
12. Rb1
{ Just removing the Rook from the attack. White is objectively winning. } 12...
Bxc4
{ This is a tricky position. Note that Black threatens ...Qe3+ and White has only one decent response. }
13. Qa4+ { The idea of this move is to play Qa3 next ! } 13... Nd7 14. Qa3
{ White consolidated. All of Black's attempts to muddy the waters will lead nowhere. }
14... Qc2 15. Nd4 Qxa2 16. Qxa2 Bxa2 17. Rb2 Nde5 18. Rxa2
{ Two pieces advantage should be enough ! Black could safely resign here. }
18... Rd8 19. N2f3 Nd3+ 20. Ke2 Nxb4 21. Rxa7 c5 22. Bd2 e5 23. Nf5 Nc6 24. Rc7
Nd4+ 25. N3xd4 exd4 26. Nxg7+ Kf8 27. Rf1 Kxg7 28. Rfxf7+ Kg6 29. Rg7+
{ A nice demonstration of White's chances when Black goes for a wrong variation. It won't surprise me if a month after this repertoire is published someone pastes a game where he has beaten someone with 9. b4. Also, note that there was a 2200+ player behind the Black pieces with a strength of a candidate master, so you should definitely expect to collect come scalps on lower levels ! }
