1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O c5 5. d3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. e4 b6 8. Re1
Bb7 9. c3
{ In the theoretical section I've mentioned why I prefer  9.a3  over this move.  In a nutshell, White wants to go for a2-a3, c2-c3 followed by b2-b4 if Black castles long. But if he changes plans and castles short, then i don't like my pawn being on c3, because it is a hook for Black's counterplay with ...b6-b5-b4. }
9... Qc7 10. a3 dxe4 11. dxe4 O-O 12. Nc4 Rad8 13. Qb3
{ I like this idea. Before committing to the kingside attack White tries to stabilize a situation on the queenside. }
13... Qc8 14. e5
{ I'd prefer to start with  14.a4  and only then switch to e4-e5. I like a4 for two reasons: 1  it stops any ...b5 ideas forever; 2  it secures our Knight's position. Black doesn't have too many decent options and I'd love to make all of the useful moves before going for the central expansion. }
14... Ne8 { I think that the more natural 14... Nd7 was stronger. } 15. Bg5
{ White combines development with weakening Black on the dark squares. If the Bishops will be exchanged, then it will be easier for White to create an attack.   Once again  15.a4  was worth considering. }
15... h6 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Rad1 Bd5 18. Qa4
{ I think I won't be too original if I say that I would strongly consider a4. }
18... Qb8 19. Ne3 { Black will have to part with the light-squared Bishop. }
19... b5 20. Nxd5 { Who said we always have to retreat ?! } 20... Nxd5
{ If  20...bxa4  then Black loses too much material after  21.Nxe7+  Kh7  22.Nc6  followed by Nxd8 with a big advantage for White. }
