{ Switching to the kingside. Black's pawn structure on the queenside is weakened and White has more space. }
21... Nec7 22. Nd2
{ Another excellent move. If you think about the position from the process of elimination perspective, then it is quite easy to find it. White's Rooks are perfectly placed, so is our Queen. Our Bishop on g2 is also good and there are no obvious pawn breaks. There is only the Knight on f3 left to be improved. So we play Nd2 and press the clock. }
22... Na8 { Black wants to relocate his Knight to b6 but it is slow. } 23. Ne4
{ Worth considering was  23.Be4  with the idea of Bc2 and Qe4. It would be surprisingly unpleasant for Black to defend against our threat of mate. }
23... Qxe5 24. Nxc5 Qc7 25. Na6 { White wants to relocate his Knight to b4. }
25... Qc8 26. Nb4 Nab6 27. Nxd5 exd5
{ Black has a permanent weakness on d5. Also, it is an open position so the Bishop is better than the Knight. We can add the fact that all of our major pieces are better placed and it is obvious that White has a big positional advantage. }
28. Rd4 { White prepares to double on the d-file. } 28... Qf5 29. Be4
{ White improves his Bishop using the fact that the d8-Rook is not protected enough. }
29... Qd7 30. Red1 Qe6 31. Qh5 f5 32. Bg2
{ White should be happy about provoking ...f5. } 32... Rd7 33. Qf3 a6 34. Qd3
Rfd8 35. Kf1
{ Black has problems finding a move. White can improve hi position further with h2-h4 and maybe h4-h5. }
35... Kh8 36. Bh3 Rf8 37. Bg2 Rfd8 38. Bh3
{ It is always nice to repeat moves. It shows that you are the one that has full control over the position and your opponent is begging for a draw. It is very often psychologically depressing for a defender. You feel like prey and your opponent is a hunter. }
38... Rf7 39. Re1 Qd6
{ Black cracks under pressure. It was better to play 39... Qf6 but White would reply with f2-f4 and put the Rook on e5. }
40. Bxf5 Qf8 41. g4 g6 42. Bxg6 { Not fearing any ghosts. } 42... Rxf2+ 43. Kg1
Rxb2 44. Rf1 { 44.Qg3  was cleaner. } 44... Qd6 45. Rdf4 Nd7 46. Qd4+ Qe5 47.
Rf5 Qxd4+ 48. cxd4 Nb6
