{ I like this continuation. If White would play  21.h6  then after  21...g5 !  Black gets some counterplay. }
21... d4 22. Nf5
{ Kasparow once stated that 'whenever you are able to get the Knight to f5 it is worth sacrificing a pawn'. Here, White didn't sacrifice anything and Black has to be very careful about Qg4/Bh6/h6 ideas. I think that objectively Black may be simply busted. }
22... Ra6 23. Qg4 g6 24. Rac1
{ White doesn't have to rush. Bojkov's advantage is not tactical but a positional one. So here, he improves the worst placed piece - the a1-Rook. }
24... Re6 25. Re4 Re8
{ Black threatens ...Bf8 with an annoying pressure on the e5-pawn, so it is a decision time for White. }
26. hxg6 Rxg6
{ 26...hxg6  was the only chance but White gets a strong attack anyway after  27.Kg2.  followed by Rh1. }
27. Nh6+ Kg7 28. Qf5 Rf8 29. Kg2 { Preparing Rh1 - it is over. } 29... Bg5 30.
Rh1 Bxf4
{ 30...Bxh6  31.Bxh6+  Rxh6  32.Rxh6  Kxh6  33.Rh4+  certainly doesn't help Black. }
31. Rxf4 { 31.Qxf4  freeing the f5-square for the Knight was even stronger. }
31... Qe7 32. Qh5 Qxe5 33. Nf5+ Kf6 34. Qh4+
{ Black threw the towel. A nice illustration of White's chances in the KIA. Another game in which one inaccuracy from Black has a huge impact on the whole game. }
