{ I didn't have time to prepare for this game so I decided that I will give the KIA set-up another chance. }
1. g3 d5 2. Bg2 c6 3. d3 Nf6 4. Nd2
{ 4. Nf3 is considered to be stronger because it stops ...e5. } 4... e5 5. Ngf3
Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. e4 Bg4
{ Black developed his pieces very harmoniously and he enjoys the perfect Caro-Kann set-up. }
8. b3
{ My recommendation is 8. h3 which you can check out in the KIA vs Caro-Kann with 3... e5 chapter. }
8... Nbd7 9. Bb2 Re8 10. Re1 Qc7 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4
{ I like this plan but it was more accurate to take on  d5  first. After  12.exd5  cxd5  we can continue with  13.g4  and   12.exd5  Nxd5  has less venom now because the f4-square hasn't been weakened yet. }
12... Bg6 13. Nh4
{ Now it is too late for  13.exd5  because  13...Nxd5 !  would lead to problems for White. }
13... dxe4 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4
{ 16. dxe4? would be a positional mistake because White would block his light-squares Bishop and Black can play ...Nd7-c5-e6 and probably ...Nf4 next. }
16... Nf6 17. Qf3
{ White has a pair of Bishops while Black enjoys a better pawn structure. }
17... Rad8 18. Re2 Bb4
{ A mysterious move. Black probably wanted to stop Rae1 but this Bishop won't be stable on the queenside. }
19. Qg3 { I wanted to play d4. } 19... Rd7 20. Kh1
{ Stepping away from the dark squares. I want to play Rf1 followed by f4. }
20... Rde7 21. Rf1 Nd5 22. Bxd5
{ This Knight has to be taken. Otherwise, it would be too strong on f4. } 22...
cxd5 23. c4 Qd6 24. Kg1
{ Now, when all of my plans connected with f4 aren't attractive any more, I decided to bring my King back to the centre. }
24... dxc4 25. dxc4 f6
{ It was much better to play 26. Bc3 or 26. Ra1 trying to force a3 + b4 plan. }
26. Qe3 Rd8 27. Qxa7
{ After this move, I should lose. I completely underestimated the danger to my King, when my Queen went pawn-grabbing and I should be punished. }
27... Bc5 28. Qa5 b6
{ 28... Red7 followed by ...e4 should guarantee Black a victory. After the text move, White can regroup and is back in the game. }
29. Qc3 Red7 { 29... e4 ! was necessary to keep an advantage. } 30. Qc2
{ It was necessary to take control over some light squares with 30. Qf3 or 30. Kg2. I thought that I control everything now and I remember being quite optimistic about my chances. As usual, when everything seems to work quite well, there comes an unwanted guest whose name is Mr Tactics and spoils the whole party. }
30... Kf7
{ Returning the favour.  30...e4 !  was an excellent move with the point being  31.Qxe4 ??  Re7  32.Qf3  Rxe2 !  and White's Queen is overloaded.  33.Qxe2  Qg3+  is curtains.   After  30...e4  I would need to play something like  31.Kg2  but Black builds up his attack with  31...f5 !  and White is in big trouble. }
31. Qe4 Qe6 32. Kg2
{ The dust has settled and what I need to do is to convert my extra pawn. But firstly, White needs to consolidate. 32. Kg2 is a natural move stepping away from any issues on the dark-squares. }
32... Bd4 33. Rd1
{ One of the basic positional rules is to exchange pieces only when it serves some positive purpose. Here, I don't mind the exchanges, but I want to do it on my terms. }
33... f5 34. Qf3 Bxb2 35. Rxd7+ Rxd7 36. Rxb2
{ By exchanging a pair of Rooks, I eased my defensive task. Now the d-file control is not so important because it is quite unlikely that Black will create any dangerous threats with his two remaining heavy pieces - three would be a different story. That's why I really like 33. Rd1. }
36... Qd6
{ Black was in time trouble and he forgot about his f-pawn. It was necessary to strengthen Black's position with something like ...Qf6. }
37. gxf5 { Now everything is easy. } 37... Kg8 38. fxg6 Qxg6+ 39. Qg4 Qxg4+ 40.
hxg4 Kf7 41. Kf3 Kf6 42. Ke3 Ke6 43. Rd2 Ra7 44. a4
{ Followed by Rd5-b5 and a5 or c5. Another tough game which indicated that still a lot of work has to be done to play the KIA confidently. On the other hand, even nowadays I consider the set-up with ...d5 ...c6 ...Nf6 and ...Bg4  (which I like to call the reversed Torre)  to be the best for Black vs the 1. Nf3 2. g3 move order. That's why I prefer to go for the Reti set-up after 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 whenever I choose the 1. Nf3 move order. }
