{ This is one of my favourite games in the KIA. It convinced me that even 2200 players can completely lose track in our favourite opening. }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. d3 d6 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. a4
{ I like this space gaining move. It doesn't give away any of our plans to our opponents and we keep our position flexible. Also, Black needs to tell us some secrets about his plan. }
8... Rb8 9. Nc4
{ Black wants to go for the ...a6 followed by ...b5 break.   It is good to put our Knight on  c4  because after  9...a6  we may consider  10.a5  Be6  11.Nfd2  taking control over the queenside. }
9... Bg4
{ I don't like this move. White should be able to gain an upper hand after simple measures. }
10. h3 { 10.Ne3  was also interesting. } 10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nd7
{ My opponent wanted to exchange some pieces to ease his task. I decided not to be too cooperative. }
12. Bg2 Nde5 13. Ne3
{ As I already mentioned two games ago, I like to do exchanges when they serve me some purpose. Here, any of them would suit Black. }
13... a6 14. h4
{ It is an interesting plan for White. I think we should always consider it whenever the Black Knight abandons the kingside. A more obvious plan was to go for 14. f4 using the fact, that Black's Knight is misplaced on e5. }
14... Nd7 15. h5
{ Now Black has a guessing game: Will he prepare h5-h6 ? Will he take on g6 ? Or is he going to stand there and irritate me for eternity ? }
15... Nf6 { Forcing me to make up my mind. } 16. hxg6 hxg6
{ Afer  16...fxg6  Black would weaken the light squares too much.  17.c3  followed by Qb3 would guarantee White a large advantage. }
17. f4
{ Black's King has been weakened so it is a good idea to build up on the kingside. }
17... Nd7
{ Note the Black Knight's journey in this game: g8-f6-d7-e5-d7-f6-d7. A hard-working mustang ! }
18. c3
{ Taking control over the d4-square and preparing Qb3 which can be useful in many cases. }
18... e6 19. Bh3
{ I wanted to play f4-f5 but I decided to strengthen it first. } 19... f5
{ Black relies on the light-squared blockade but it can't work. } 20. Qb3
{ 20.exf5  gxf5  21.g4  was also good enough. } 20... Qe7
{ This move allows White to execute a nice tactical sequence. } 21. exf5 gxf5
22. Nxf5
{ 22.Bxf5  c4  23.Qxc4  d5  24.Nxd5  exd5  25.Qxd5+  was even stronger. } 22...
Rxf5 23. Bxf5 c4 24. Qxc4 d5 25. Qa2 exf5 26. Qxd5+ Qf7 27. Qxf7+ Kxf7
{ Now, when the dust has settled, we should analyse the resulting position. White has the Rook and three pawns for two minor pieces. In the middlegame, it may be difficult to evaluate but endgames are simpler. In this position, it is all about control. White controls all of the important central squares. If, for example, our c-pawn would be on c4 instead of c3 then White would be in trouble due to some ...Nd4 and ...Nc5 ideas. Here it is not a problem. }
28. Be3
{ Ideally we want to exchange as many stuff as possible to avoid any problems. In this position, we can somehow imagine Black creating anything, but if we exchange everything, then White will have a Rook + 3 pawns vs two minor pieces only - Black would be completely busted. }
28... Re8 29. Rfe1 Bf8 30. Bf2 Bc5
{ Remember me mentioning exchanges on our terms ? So now I get everything I wanted. I manage to exchange two sets of pieces and the rest will be easy. Black should keep as many pieces as possible and somehow try to create threats. }
31. Rxe8 Bxf2+ { Even improving my King. } 32. Kxf2 Kxe8 33. b4
{ Taking away more squares from Black Knights. } 33... Ne7 34. c4
{ Now we take control over the d5-square. } 34... Nf6 35. a5 Nc6 36. b5 Ng4+
37. Kg2 Nb4 38. Rh1
{ The easiest plan. We give up a pawn but Black will be defenceless. } 38...
Nxd3 39. Rh7 { Cutting off the Black King. } 39... Kd8 40. Rxb7 Ne3+ 41. Kh3
{ 41. Kf3 was probably even better but I wanted to avoid any calculations. White is winning anyway. }
