Qc7 9. e5 Nd7 10. Qe2 b5 11. Nf1 a5 12. Bf4 Ba6
{ Both sides followed their normal plans. } 13. h4 b4 14. Ne3
{ The is the extra option that we have against the ... Qc7 lines. White wants to take on d5 followed by e6. }
14... Nb6
{ A risky move. The problem is that the Knight is now far from the kingside and it will be tougher for Black to withstand the pressure on that side of the board. }
15. h5
{ Starting with 15. Ng4 was probably stronger, because I wouldn't have to worry that much about any ... Nd4 ideas.   15.Ng5 !  was the probably the strongest move preparing Qh5 next. }
15... h6
{ Black is obliged to stop h6 from White. I remember that it took my opponent some time to play this move. I was walking through the playing hall hoping he will not play that ! }
16. Ng4 Rfc8
{ The strongest move clearing the f8-square for the Bishop and preparing counterplay via the c-file. }
17. Qd2 Qd8
{ At this point, I knew that the ideas connected with Bxh6 don't work, but I needed some resource that would strengthen my attack.   17...Bf8 ?  18.Bxh6 !  gxh6  19.Nxh6+  Kh8   19...Bxh6  20.Qxh6  Nd7  21.Ng5  Nf8  Now we see the biggest drawback of ... Nb6 - the Knight had to go back.  22.f4  +-  G4 and f5 are next with a devastating attack.  20.Qg5  Bg7  21.Qf4  ±  would lead to a very strong attack for White. Ng4 and h6 are next. }
18. Bh3
{ And I found it ! This move brings the Bishop to the action by pressurizing e6, which will be crucial for the attack to succeed. }
18... Nd4
{ This is a mistake that allowed me to carry through my attacking ideas.   18...Bf8  was the best defence but White would still have a strong attack.  19.Ngh2 !  Clearing the way for the g-pawn !  c4  20.g4  →  White's attack is running by itself. }
