22... Kxf7 23. Qh6
{ Despite being two pieces down, Black will deliver series of critical blos with the remaining units. Black loses no matter what. }
23... Bg5
{ 23...Ke8  24.Bxe6   23...Qh8  24.Bxe6+  Ke8  25.Qxh8+   23...Qf8  24.Qg6#   23...Qd7  24.Qg6+  Kf8  25.Bxe6 }
24. Qh7+ { There were many ways forward, but I found this one the cleanest. }
24... Ke8 25. Bxe6 Qe7 26. Qg8+ Qf8 27. Qg6+
{ Forcing the King on the dark square. I will be able to get a ton of material back. }
27... Ke7 28. Bxc8 Rxc8 29. Qxg5+ Kd7 30. e6+
{ Now the Rook and the pawn join the action. } 30... Kc6 31. e7 Qf7 32. Qg6+
{ The simplest. } 32... Qxg6 33. hxg6 Kd7 34. e8=Q+ Rxe8 35. Rxe8 Kxe8 36. Re1+
Kf8 37. Re6
{ The pieces that should enable Black a counterplay on the queenside, twenty moves later bring only sorrow. One of my best KIA games. }
